{
    "attributes": {
        "action": "Fast-track access to benefits for terminally ill as soon as diagnosed",
        "additional_details": "Terminally ill people who are expected to live longer than twelve months are being excluded by the Government from special rules enabling fast-tracking of applications. Claims can take months and when you\u2019re diagnosed the last thing you need is a fight to get your benefits.\r\n \r\nThe failure to fast-track access to benefits for anyone diagnosed with a terminal illness causes unnecessary suffering to people who have been told they are going to die. As soon a person is diagnosed they should automatically be fast-tracked. Why must a time scale be placed?\r\n \r\nTerminal means terminal however long you have left to live.",
        "background": "The current special rules for terminal illness say fast-track benefit applications are only available for those with a terminal diagnosis of 12 months. I feel this is penalising people with a terminal diagnosis  but who are not expected to die in the next twelve months.",
